法規內容.條文內容:
When applying for the production and issuance, change or replacement of the NHI IC Card, the beneficiary shall fill out an application form and comply with the following requirements:
1. Where an application is made by the applicant himself or herself in person, the original identification document shall be presented to the insurer for verification;
2. Where an application is made by another person or a group insurance applicant entrusted by the applicant, the original identification documents of the applicant and the entrusted person shall be presented to the insurer for verification;
3. Where an application is made via post or the Entrusted Institution, the identification document shall be submitted to the insurer for verification.
4. Where an application is made online, the citizen digital certificate and digital certificate of the entity issued by the respective industry competent authorities shall be used to log into the insurer’s global information website to proceed with the application.
The identification document set forth in the preceding paragraph refers to one of the following documents:
1. National identification card: household registration certificate may replace the national identification card in the case of a person under the age of 14 years old;
2. Passport issued by the Republic of China;
3. Driver’s license of automobile (motorcycle); or
4. Alien resident certificate in compliance with Article 8 of the Enforcement Rules of the National Health Insurance Act.

Where any of the following circumstances occurs, the NHI IC Card of a beneficiary shall be updated at the NHI IC Card reader installed in the contracted medical care institutions or the insurer:
1. The NHI IC Card expires or has zero credit for medical treatment;
2. The beneficiary acquires or loses the status of a low-income household member, veteran, household representative of survivors of veterans;
3. The proof of major illness and injury of the beneficiary is acquired, revoked or cancelled upon the notice of the insurer;
4. The registration and change of organ donation or hospice palliative care; or
5. Any other medical need which is recorded.
Where the insurer provides medical visit advice to a beneficiary, it may request the beneficiary to update his or her credits for medical treatment at a designated place.

The insurer may only use the data keyed in and uploaded from the contracted medical care institutions for the following purposes:
1. Management and audit of abnormal medical visits of beneficiaries or abnormal diagnosis and treatment behaviors of physicians;
2. Real-time advice for beneficiaries who are high users of medical services;
3. Management of abnormal drug use by beneficiaries; and
4. Coordination with disease prevention and health related policies.
